I will acknowledge Barry Spatz's question as being legitimate as I have to admit ignorance to what actually happened from the birds-eye view of those on the ground, versus what was depicted by the media. However, what had impressed me was Tom's post about his father and what Tom had inherited from his him. In 1984, I first heard of the term, second generation PTSD, but have rarely heard of it since, thus, is this an actual phenomenon? Or is it something that just legitimizes a veterans behavior? I truely do not know, but there is a tie in with John's post regarding compromising our own belief's and values.<br><br>
I also grew up in a home as Tom described, my father a wounded WWII vet who ignored and denied much, even in the face of his obvious behavior towards his kid. The fact that he was a vet and that my uncle, my role model, was also a wounded vet defininately had contributed to my decision to volunteer for the draft. In regards to John's theory, I believe that he could extend that the contributing factor was not that we compromised our own beliefs and values, but that in some form, we were trying to live up to other's expectations. I say this from personal experiences only. When I told my father of my volunteering for the draft, he reacted angerly and violently. I showed up at Fort Ord with a black eye, chipped tooth, split lip and the like. This was probably the first contradiction to my desicion that I was confronted with. Others were that when I went in, there was a unspoken ackowledgement from the community that I was doing what was expected of me, and when I came back I was confronted by a whole new set of expectations. Never mind all those contradictions I came across while in 'Nam. Contradictions is probably more apt term than compromise, however, they may be separate and distinctive issues. These posts have raised more questions than answers. Damn. I would like to get more feedback on this from John and Tom and anybody else, please.
